{"key":"processedPost-9931450","value":{"id":9931450,"first":9929033,"last":9938871,"when":1236493138,"utime":"03/08/09 09:18 AM","content":"With proper air exchange, you can keep the humidity high through fruiting for nicer fruits and more primordia.&nbsp; If you have problems getting enough fresh air to your crop, lower the humidity.&nbsp; A good rule of thumb is that if you mist and the fruits are dry in fifteen minutes or so, you have enough fresh air.&nbsp; If they're still wet after fifteen minutes, increase fresh air.<br /><br />It's always a good idea to reduce humidity the day your pick.&nbsp; Often I'll set a tray outside the grow area for a few hours to let the fruits dry somewhat before picking.&nbsp; This makes them stay fresh longer after picking, if stored in a paper bag in the refrigerator.<br />RR","title":"Re: Lower rh at this point? PICS","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}